pageSummaryWhat: A photo with with/somewhere with every letter!
pageSummaryWhy: Macmillan helps many with cancer every year
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. 

I am completing the ‘Alphapet Challenge’ with my dogs Bailey (12) and Coco (17 weeks as we start!) I will be taking a photo of them with something or somewhere for every single letter of the alphabet whilst encouraging you all to donate for such an amazing charity. 

When it comes to cancer nobody is untouchable and you never know if/when you may need help from charities such as Macmillan to support yourself or your family at a time of need. With Covid having taken a major toll on cancer patients and their families: making them unable to get appointments, having to strictly shield, getting later diagnosis and so much more- it is more important than ever to support charities like these.

Any donations no matter how small are appreciated 

 ‘’Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. pageSummary: I am going to walk 300kms during this 2nd lockdown because I want to support cancer patients and families
pageSummaryWhat: I am going to walk 300kms during this 2nd lockdown
pageSummaryWhy: I want to support cancer patients and families
story:
I am going to walk 300+kms (about 200 miles) during this second lockdown to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support. This wonderful charity provides physical, financial and emotional support to cancer patients and their loved ones and helps them live life as fully as they can.

During this 2nd lockdown I am also thinking of the impact of this virus on everyone. We are all struggling with different issues and to different degrees - money, isolation, mental and physical health etc. It is more important than ever at the moment to get out and spend time in nature, even if it is only a few hundred yards a day or a walk around the block.

I have found that walking in the fresh air has helped me enormously in recent weeks. I am not particularly fit or sporty and I have always lacked energy! I also hate walking in the rain!!!! So I have set myself a goal to help others and to motivate myself to greater levels of fitness.

Why not join me by Walking for Wellness too as well as donating to Macmillan Cancer Support? We need to care for others but also look after our wellbeing. So put on your coat and shoes and get outside, but before you do click on the link below!

pageSummary: Rather than flowers, we wanted to ask a donation because this helps care for people suffering from Cancer.
pageSummaryWhat: Rather than flowers, we wanted to ask a donation
pageSummaryWhy: this helps care for people suffering from Cancer.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page. In these difficult times, we wanted to ask, rather than send flowers, we would appreciate a donation instead, to a charity we feel would benefit others. We chose Macmillan. 

Dad eventually succumbed to mesothelioma and while there's no cure for this, your donation would help in giving palliative care to others. It would also give comfort to us, his family.

Doing this through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe - they'll never sell them on or send you unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity.

Thanks again for taking the time to do this, and for letting us know that you are thinking about him and us at this time.

pageSummary: I am raising money because my mum sadly lost her battle with cancer
pageSummaryWhy: my mum sadly lost her battle with cancer
story:
This is a Just Giving page, set up in memory of Lynn Kirkland who sadly lost her battle with cancer on 24th October 2020.

We have chosen to raise money for two different charities:- MacMillan Cancer Support and Kilbryde Hospice. 

We kindly asked for no flowers at the funeral and instead, requested any donations made to our chosen charities. Both of these charities were close to my mums heart and have also supported us throughout this difficult time.

We would like to do something positive during our time of sadness and would therefore be very greatful for any donations made to help us raise money for these two organisations. 

Thank you very much for your support.

Gillian

xxx

pageSummary: Sadly passed away too soon after a Cancer Battle because they cared for him with dignity until the very end
pageSummaryWhat: Sadly passed away too soon after a Cancer Battle
pageSummaryWhy: they cared for him with dignity until the very end
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Our fantastic fun loving devoted husband, father and grandfather sadly was taken too soon. After a mammoth battle with Cancer it finally got the better of him and was put on palliative care and had dignity until the bitter thanks to the wonderful NHS and Macmillan Nurses.  

We would ask that instead of sending any cards, flowers etc to the family or sending any flowers to his funeral that we just each put a little bit of money in and send to this amazing charity

Cancer has touched us all in some way or another and we may all need them at some stage!

Thank you very much everyone x

pageSummary: I will be running lots in 2021 in memory of my dad because My father passed away in 2019 due to heart issues
pageSummaryWhat: I will be running lots in 2021 in memory of my dad
pageSummaryWhy: My father passed away in 2019 due to heart issues
story:
Hi there,  in 2021 i will be setting myself a mamouth task to run 52 half marathon distances, 52 10k distances and 52 5k distances in 52 weeks! I must be mad. I will be doing this in memory of my father, Kevin, who sadly passed away in July 2019 due to major heart issues. This is why i have chosen to raise money for the British Heart Foundation.

My father was a hard working man, even after suffering 4 major heart attacks he continued to work right up to retirement at 67 years of age! He loved his family and loved all of his grandchildren and we all adored him and loved him.  

He eventually made the move to live with me & my wife and his 2 grandchildren in somerset  so we could look after him as his heart was causing him problems.  Even though this was only to be for a short period, i remember the fun he had with us and his grandchildren,  the laughter & the smiles while playing table football. Him lifting one end of the football table so he would win😂 all great memories.  Him shouting at the tv when spurs werent doing too well. He was a huge tottenham fan( like myself)

One weekend in July 2019, my dad decided he wanted to go back to his home in London to collect his last possesions. I drove him home and returned 2 days later to a scene that will live with me and my family forever. My  12 year old son charlie ran in to see his grandad, to discover he had passed away. I wish i could have protected my son from this image. This is an image that will live with us forever.  If i could turn back time i would never have left my dad, and its gutting that we never had our chance to say goodbye.  

But i know my dad, and i know that he wouldnt want us moping around and being upset. He would want us to keep on going, keep on strong, keep on fighting & living.....thats exactly what i intend to do! 

I do have a liking for running so in a way to remember my dad, i have decided to set myself this challenge to keep my mind and body in tune and to raise money for a cause which may help to prevent further events like this for someone else

It will be a gruelling year physically & mentally but my dad and my family will be my motivating factor. I will be running half marathon, 10k & 5k distances and hopefully a few races will reopen in 2021 if Covid19 does one! I have no time frames but i would be happy if i could hit a 1hr 35min half marathon, a 45 min 10k & a 21 min 5k? 

Thanks for reading my story and thanks for all of your support & donations. Any donation will be hugely appreciated! 

This is for you dad, Kevin Hedges , BIG K 1950 - 2019
title: 52 halfs, 10ks & 5ks in 52 weeks

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. I lost my dad in April 2016 to a cardiac arrest, myself and my brother were with him at the time and it’s something I wouldn’t wish on anybody. Anyone who knew dad wouldn’t say he was the perfect patient over the years but  also a fighter and an amazing dad.  Unfortunately I was very ill in June 2018 and the amazing cardiac and respiratory unit saved my life. This was a hereditary condition and one I have adapted too. But as a result I am determined not end up like dad and I need to be fit healthy and well and live a long life. I loved running as a youngster was pretty good tbh and always wanted to do the London Marathon. This is a start to that and not begging demanding or ought like that. The  BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can continue it’s heard work.

pageSummary: Looking for a challenge because It is a worthwhile cause....
story:
100 for Guide Dogs is your challenge, your way. You can choose to Run100, Cycle100 or Swim100 between 1 July and 31 November

Ok I love cycling so I commit to  5  100 mile  rides during that period. 

I  run rarely so I commit to run either  a minimum of 100km or a max of 100 miles in that period.

I hate swimming, or more like I hate going to swimming pools so I am committing to 100 minutes a month for 5 months. 

As I am participating in 3 challenges my target is £300! So thanks for your donations and support.

£100 could pay for five hours' training at a Guide Dogs training school.It's thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services, like our guide dogs, to people with sight loss. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!#TeamGuideDogs

story:
Joanne Barker is walking to raise money for Cancer Research UK. Taking inspiration from Captain Tom, Jo is going to walk 100 LAPS OF HER ROAD by December 2nd, when lockdown ends. To the end of the road and back = 1 lap. 

Each lap is 320 metres, meaning by the time she has completed her challenge, she will have completed 32 kilometers, which is 20 miles! If this challenge wasn't taxing enough on its own, Jo also has arthritis in her knees and hips, meaning she will have to dig deep, and push through the pain barrier to complete the distance in time! Please dig deep (in your pockets) in return, and help Jo support this fantastic cause, not to mention giving her the boost she needs to make it across the line!

Thanks so much for visiting Jo's page - 

Judy (Jo's Mum)

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Emma's Story

Emma works at The Francis Crick Institute as a computational scientist and is currently working at the forefront of cancer bioinformatics on behalf of the NHS and in partnership with Cancer Research UK.

She is a PhD student, an award-winning theoretical physicist and a passionate fundraiser having led efforts to raise over £1m to date for cancer research and related causes.

At age 4, Emma tragically lost her father to lung cancer. He was a celebrated mathematician, a cherished husband and a devoted father of two young girls. 

She runs her first marathon in his enduring memory and in the hope that her current research will contribute to the better outcomes for millions of families affected by cancer.

Tom's Story

Tom is an endurance athlete, digital nomad and growth marketing specialist currently working at Just, a fintech business seeking to improve debt collection practices through technology.

Seeking an excuse to run another marathon, he has volunteered to coach Emma, fundraise together for Cancer Research UK and run alongside her as she celebrates her 30th Birthday that month.

Tom tragically lost his grandmother to lung cancer just two days before he was born. She was a cherished wife and devoted mother of three who died at the age of just 48.

He runs his third marathon in her enduring memory and in support of Emma and her colleagues, who are at the forefront of global efforts to find pioneering new treatments for cancer.

eventName: Christmas Giving for Marie Curie Bradford
story:
Christmas Giving
Claire and Janet would like to raise a little money for a fabulous Bradford Charity, Marie Curie, and we would like to also give you a little something back to hang a bit of humour on your Christmas Tree, to remind everyone of how difficult 2020 has been and to embrace Christmas the best way we can.
Christmas decorations are available for single, twos, threes, fours and fives with personalised names on hats and toilet roll at a cost of £5.00. Hopefully we can deliver to your door but anybody who wishes to order further afield, add a little bit more of a donation and we will happily pay your postage.  Delivery beginning of December.

Please donate a minimum of £5.00 and send a private message to either Claire or Janet  on Facebook with your personalised name(s) for hats and slogan for toilet roll.  This could be “Merry Christmas”, “The Year We Stayed Home” or “The Claus Family”.

Hope you will embrace our little bit or Christmas Tack to give something back xxx

pageSummary: I am raising money through a Christmas raffle because I wanted to give back after they helped my family
pageSummaryWhat: I am raising money through a Christmas raffle
pageSummaryWhy: I wanted to give back after they helped my family
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. 

One of many reasons I’m raising money for Marie Curie this Christmas. 


My family were lucky to have had the help of the Marie Curie nurses in the last couple of days of my grandpas life. We cared for him as a family at home for a long time but mostly the last few months were the hardest. We became his carers, my mum especially and she lost the father daughter relationship to a caring one. We’d been through a similar situation with my Nan 15 years ago but it seemed so much harder this time. 

Personally I’m grateful for the first lockdown as that gave me time with him that I’ll never get back. Unfortunately because of the days and hours I work I miss out on a lot of family things but that time off was precious.

When Marie Curie stepped in it gave us our time back to be his family again, his daughter, his son and his grandchildren. They practically forced my sister to switch off from being the nurse that she’s trained to be, to being his granddaughter once more.

story:
Wheels & Jigs’ take on a 30 Day Challenge!  

The 'Wheels and Jigs’ crew normally take on the astounding journey from Dromore, Co. Tyrone to Miltown Malbay, Co. Clare ‪but due the COVID-19 we had to change things up! 🙌🏻 

Starting on Friday 20th November 2020 the group of musicians will either cycle, run or row 200 miles by Saturday 19th December 2020. Wind, rain, hail or snow..... nothing will stops these lads! 

Taking part are many acclaimed musicians from all over the country, many are Wheels & Jigs regulars plus a few new faces - sure to be a fun filled adventure and maybe a tune or two! 

Since ‘Wheels & Jigs’ was founded in 2015, the cyclists have astonishingly made a significant difference to many charitable organisations and families all over Ireland. Having raised over a remarkable £18,000, ‘Wheels & Jigs’ always set out with a purpose - to raise funds for charities that will always remain close to their hearts. Thus far, Alzheimer’s, NI Children Hospice, Galway Hospice, Pieta House and Action Mental Health, Fermanagh Women’s Aid, Chest Heart & Stroke! 

This year... the cyclists set out again to raise money for the charity Marie Curie.  Marie Curie is the largest charitable provider of end of life care in Northern Ireland that help to fight the battle of these illnesses on a daily basis. Last year Marie Curie Nurses cared for over 31,558 people at home approaching the end of their life and have revealed the surge to Northern Ireland care homes during coronavirus crisis. It has been a challenging time for all nurses this year due to the difficult circumstances.

Finally, a tremendous thank you to all of the sponsors and members of the public for their generous donations and continuous support, it is immeasurably appreciated.
title: Wheels and Jigs Cycle's Wheels & Jig 30 Day Challenge

story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
As we enter this second lockdown for the UK, the closure of Oxfam shops means every week they lose £1.5 million of income - that would be enough to provide 150,000 people in vulnerable communities with lifesaving clean water, handwashing facilities and supplies for healthcare workers.

This lockdown I wanted to use the simple freedom I have to get outside for something worthwhile. On Saturday 28th November I will be walking over 40km from Richmond to Greenwich along the Thames to raise money for Oxfam.

Oxfam represents many of my core values - safe & clean water for all, women and gender justice and climate change action to name a few. Please consider supporting me and, as one of the DEC charities supporting aid for COVID-19 in vulnerable communities, every £ we donate to Oxfam together will be matched by the UK government.

Thank you so much for supporting me!

Find out more about Oxfam at www.oxfam.org.uk
title: Bella's Lockdown walk for Oxfam

story:
Thank you for visiting my page. 

This year has been really hard for me: I've missed seeing my friends and going to sports clubs during lockdown.  But for young people in the poorest countries, this year has been a lot worse.  UNICEF estimates that 6000 chidren could die every day in the next 6 months because they don't have food, clean water or medicine. 

I'm going to run a half marathon on 12th December, the week before my 13th birthday.  Your donation will go towards medical equipment, sanitation and clean water facilities and access to education for children who need it most. 

I have always wanted to help UNICEF and can't wait to run the half marathon to support this cause!
title: Christopher's half marathon for UNICEF

We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:
Theatre nurse Scarlett Brannigan is coming to Barts fo MSF to give us a view on the varied missions MSF are fighting for. 

She is currently working for COVID care London, a charity that have been active in supporting people who are homeless in east London durning the pandemic. She wants to share with us the amazing work this charity is doing and her experiences during this world pandemic 
During her time in Sokoto Nigeria she worked in a children’s hospital where she treated children who had developed a deadly and disfiguring disease called Noma.

Noma kills 1000 of people every year with very little public attention. Yet it is completely preventable. 
If you would like to find out more about Scarlett’s journey from Nigeria to the UK join us on the 16th of November for our event The varied missions on the MSF Field.

 16th November 6pm
Microsoft teams (check Facebook for tickets!)
title: Barts's From Noma to COVID-19

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
pageSummary: We are raising money with a Xmas Hamper draw because everyone should have clean water & a proper toilet
pageSummaryWhat: We are raising money with a Xmas Hamper draw
pageSummaryWhy: everyone should have clean water & a proper toilet
story:
EMEA Synergy invites you to participate in a Christmas Hamper Draw to win one of two fantastic Christmas hampers from Fortnum and Mason, whilst raising money for a great cause. 

EMEA Synergy has chosen to support WaterAid because of the work they are doing to support the most vulnerable communities in the world providing access to safe water, toilets and to help promote good hygiene. In addition, the work they do to ensure women have access to toilet facilities which reduces the risk of sexual harassment.  

Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, children are born healthier. They get the chance to go to school and grow up to become adults. Women and men get to earn a living. Whole communities start to thrive. It sounds normal and it should be.

With the COVID 19 crisis it is more important that ever to support those communities that do not have access to something that most of us take for granted.

Many thanks for your support and good luck.

EMEA Synergy
title: EMEA Synergy Christmas Hamper Draw

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. 

Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, children are born healthier. They get the chance to go to school and grow up to become adults. Women and men get to earn a living. Whole communities start to thrive. 

It sounds normal and it should be.
title: Coz
